drama film: That Forward Center Died at Dawn () is a 1961 Argentine drama film, adapted by Agustín Cuzzani from his play of the same name.

Golden Age of Argentine Cinema: It was a popular success, one of the major hits of the Golden Age of Argentine Cinema.

List of Argentine films of 1944: When Spring Makes a Mistake or Cuando la primavera se equivoca is a 1944 Argentine film directed by Mario Soffici.

cinema of Argentina: At the Sound of the Bugle () is a 1941 Argentine film directed by Orestes Caviglia and written by Florencio Chiarello.

Argentina: Crane World () is a 1999 Argentine film, written and directed by Pablo Trapero.

Brigada explosiva contra los ninjas (English language: Explosive Brigade Against the Ninjas) is a 1986 Argentine adventure comedy film directed by Miguel Fernández Alonso and written by Salvador Valverde Calvo.

Argentine Army: The army uniforms came from the Argentine Army.

Silver Spring, Maryland: Shown at the American Film Institute's Silver Theatre in Silver Spring, Maryland, on September 24, 2005, this post-modern film explores mother-daughter relationships and the struggles of a 10-year-old child to raise her cocaine-addicted mother.

fantasy film: Barbarian Queen (also known as Queen of the Naked Steel) is a 1985 American-Argentine fantasy film starring Lana Clarkson, directed by Héctor Olivera and written by Howard R. Cohen.

Cinema of Argentina: Tire dié (1960) is an Argentine documentary directed by Fernando Birri and written Birri and seven other writers.

Golden Age of Argentine Cinema: It is a tango film, an extremely popular genre during the Golden Age of Argentine Cinema.

List of Argentine films of 1950: Cinco grandes y una chica is a 1950 Argentine film.

Argentina: Cuidado Con Las Mujeres (English language:With the Music in my Soul) is a 1951 Argentine comedy film directed by Enrique Cahen Salaberry and screen written by Ariel Cortazzo based on a play by André Revesz.

drama film: Swan Song (Spanish:El canto del cisne) is a 1945 Argentine romantic drama film directed by Carlos Hugo Christensen and starring Mecha Ortiz, Roberto Escalada and Miguel Gómez Bao.

cinema of Argentina: El diablo con faldas is a Argentine drama film directed by Ivo Pelay.

Argentina: Argentina also has won seventeen Goya Awards for Best Spanish Language Foreign Film with "A King and His Movie" (1986), "A Place in the World" (1992), "Gatica, el mono" (1993), "Autumn Sun" (1996), "Ashes of Paradise" (1997), "The Lighthouse" (1998), "Burnt Money" (2000), "The Escape" (2001), "Intimate Stories" (2003), "Blessed by Fire" (2005), "The Hands" (2006), "XXY" (2007), "The Secret in Their Eyes" (2009), "Chinese Take-Away" (2011), "Wild Tales" (2014), "The Clan" (2015) and "The Distinguished Citizen" (2016), being by far the most awarded country in Latin America with twenty-four nominations.
Leyenda del puente inca (English language: Legend of the Inca Bridge) is a 1923 silent Argentine film directed and written by José A. Ferreyra.
Candida, Millionairess () is a 1941 Argentine musical comedy film directed by Luis Bayón Herrera, who adapted the Pedro E. Pico play.

List of Argentine films of 1969: Póker de amantes para tres is a 1969 Argentine film.

Argentina: Rapado is an Argentine and Dutch 1992 film, written and directed by Martín Rejtman, his first feature film.

Plumíferos (Free Birds: Flying Adventures) is a 2010 Argentine computer-animated adventure comedy film, produced by CS Entertainment, Manos Digitales Animation Studio, and 100 Bares Producciones, and was released on February 18, 2010 in Argentina.

List of Argentine films of 1964: Cuidado con las colas is a 1964 Argentine film directed by Julio Saraceni and starring Juan Carlos Thorry and Ambar La Fox.
